# self_eating_loop.gob
# The most important GobbleScript lesson: GOBBLE (@) inside a loop is a
# loaded gun, because the loop's body is re-read from the SAME instruction
# list every pass -- and that list can shrink between passes.
#
# This loop sets a counter to the character '5' (53) and *looks* like it
# should print '5','4','3','2','1' -- five digits, one per decrement, the
# way the same loop would behave in ordinary Brainfuck.
#
# Loop body, read once: .  -  @  .
#   .   print the counter
#   -   decrement the counter
#   @   gobble (permanently delete) whatever instruction comes right after it
#   .   print the counter again
#
# Pass 1: prints '5', decrements to 52, then '@' eats the trailing '.' --
#         it's gone forever, the body is now just  .  -  @  (3 instructions).
# Pass 2: prints '4', decrements to 51, then '@' fires again -- but its
#         victim THIS time isn't a '.' anymore (that one's already dead).
#         The body has shrunk enough that the very next thing in the source
#         is the loop's own closing ']'. @ eats the bracket. The loop has no
#         way to close, so it simply isn't a loop anymore -- the program
#         just runs off the end and halts.
#
# Net result: a "print 5 digits" loop that prints exactly two digits, every
# single time you run it, because it ate its own exit before it could take
# a third lap. Nothing here is random -- @ is the one chaos operator that's
# perfectly deterministic. It's just deterministic about destroying things.
+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++[.-@.]
